---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Aside from '../../../components/Aside.astro';
import {mathsSidebar} from '../../../data/maths-sidebar';
import {Code} from 'astro:components';
import {dep, mavenCentralUrl} from '../../../data/site';
---

<DocsLayout title="Getting Started with Maths" sidebar={mathsSidebar}
            description="Set up Maths in your Kotlin project">

    <h1>Getting Started</h1>

    <p class="text-xl text-gray-400 !mt-2 !mb-8">
        Add Maths to your project and start using easing functions and distributions.
    </p>

    <h2>1. Add the dependency</h2>

    <p>In your <code>build.gradle.kts</code>:</p>

    <Code code={`dependencies {
    implementation("${dep.maths}")
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <p>Find the latest version on <a href={mavenCentralUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Maven Central</a>.</p>

    <p>Maths is a Kotlin Multiplatform library &mdash; it works in <code>commonMain</code>, <code>jvmMain</code>,
        <code>jsMain</code>, and <code>nativeMain</code> (linuxX64, linuxArm64, macosX64, macosArm64, mingwX64).</p>

    <h2>2. Use an easing function</h2>

    <p>All easing functions live on the <code>Ease</code> object. Pass a progress value between 0.0 and 1.0:</p>

    <Code code={`import io.peekandpoke.ultra.maths.Ease

// Ease a progress value (0.0 to 1.0)
val eased = Ease.Out.cubic(0.5)  // 0.875

// Use calc() to ease between two values
val opacity = Ease.calc(
    from = 0.0,
    to = 1.0,
    progress = 0.5,
    fn = Ease.InOut.sine,
)  // 0.5`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>3. Bind to a range</h2>

    <p>Use <code>bindFromTo</code> to create a reusable easing bound to a numeric range:</p>

    <Code code={`val fadeIn = Ease.Out.quad.bindFromTo(from = 0, to = 255)

println(fadeIn(0.0))   // 0.0
println(fadeIn(0.5))   // 191.25
println(fadeIn(1.0))   // 255.0`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>4. Time-based easing</h2>

    <p>Use <code>timed()</code> to create an easing that progresses based on elapsed wall-clock time:</p>

    <Code code={`import kotlin.time.Duration.Companion.milliseconds

val anim = Ease.Out.elastic.timed(
    from = 0,
    to = 100,
    duration = 800.milliseconds,
)

// Poll the current value (uses Kronos clock internally)
val current = anim()

// Check if the animation has completed
if (anim.isDone) {
    // final value reached
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <Aside>Timed easing uses the <a href="/ultra/datetime/kronos">Kronos</a> clock, so you can inject a
        test clock and advance time manually in unit tests.
    </Aside>

    <h2>5. Sample a distribution</h2>

    <Code code={`import io.peekandpoke.ultra.maths.stochastic.BucketedDistribution
import io.peekandpoke.ultra.maths.stochastic.sample
import kotlin.random.Random

// Normal distribution centered at 0.5
val normal = BucketedDistribution.createTruncatedNormal(mean = 0.5, std = 0.15)

// Raw sample in [0, 1]
val raw = normal.sample(Random)

// Mapped to a custom range
val damage = normal.sample(Random, from = 10.0, to = 50.0)`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <div class="not-prose mt-8 flex gap-4">
        <a href="/ultra/maths/easing"
           class="inline-flex items-center px-6 py-3 bg-brand-600 text-white font-semibold rounded-lg hover:bg-brand-500 transition-colors">
            Easing functions &rarr;
        </a>
    </div>

</DocsLayout>
